ce:section.ce:para:
To identify the reactive species responsible for MO dye degradation and evaluate the role of scavengers in removing the dye, photocatalytic experiments were conducted under identical conditions in the presence of different scavengers: ethylenediaminetetraacetate (EDTA), isopropyl alcohol, and 1,4-benzoquinone (BQ). The results are depicted in Fig. S7a and S7b. The addition of EDTA, a scavenger for h+ radicals, reduced the photocatalytic efficiency from 99 % to 75.69 %, highlighting the significant role of holes (h+) in the degradation process. In contrast, isopropyl alcohol, a scavenger for hydroxyl radicals (OH∙), caused a smaller reduction in efficiency, from 99 % to 88.25 %, indicating that OH∙ radicals also contribute to the degradation of MO dye. The use of BQ, a scavenger for superoxide radicals (O2−​), resulted in the most pronounced reduction, from 99 % to 61.36 %, underscoring the crucial role of O2−​ in the photocatalytic mechanism. The findings indicate that h+ and O2−​ are the primary reactive species driving the degradation of MO dye, with O2−
                         playing the dominant role (Fig. S7c). Upon light irradiation, the photocatalyst generates electron-hole pairs. The conduction band electrons reduce dissolved oxygen to form highly oxidative superoxide radicals (O2−
                        ), which attack the azo bond in MO dye, leading to its breakdown and degradation. This mechanism confirms the significant role of active species in the enhanced photocatalytic activity of CDs/MoO3:1 %La3+ NCs [87].
